article.description: Kelly Roysland scored 15 points, including 10 straight in a key two-minute span, to lift Minnesota (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP)  to a 74-57 victory over Drake on Thursday.
article.headline: McCarville led Gophers with 21 points
article.linkText: Roysland comes off the bench to lift Gophers
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- In two minutes, Kelly Roysland did what her
teammates had failed to do all night -- seal a victory for
Minnesota.

Roysland scored 10 of her 15 points in a two-minute span in the
second half to lift Minnesota (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) to a 74-57 victory over Drake
on Thursday.

Roysland came off the bench to give the Gophers a much-needed
spark against the pesky Bulldogs (5-4), who trailed by 21 in the
first half but whittled the lead down to three with an 18-0 run
that spanned halftime.

Minnesota (9-2) clung to a 46-40 lead with 15 minutes to play
when Roysland went on a personal 10-0 run, hitting two 3-pointers
and two driving layups on four consecutive possessions. Drake
didn't came closer than 11 points the rest of the way.

"I think I got kind of lucky," said Roysland, who came within
one point of her career high. "I got some great passes from April
Calhoun and Shannon Bolden, and they were able to create openings
for me and give me the liberty to hit a couple of open shots. My
teammates did all the work -- I was just the one who ended up
finishing the plays."

Senior all-America center Janel McCarville led the Gophers with
21 points and 11 rebounds, while Jamie Broback added 11 points and
10 boards, but unlike recent games, the Gophers got key
contributions from their backcourt. Besides Roysland's 15, Shannon
Schonrock scored 11 points, and Calhoun added six points and six
assists.

"The coaches have been stressing to all us guards that we need
more scoring on the perimeter," Roysland said. "We can't depend
on (McCarville and Broback) to score 25 points a game for us. We
need to make them defend us on the perimeter to open things up for
them inside."

That formula worked to perfection for the Gophers in the second
half. After Roysland's spurt softened Drake's defense, McCarville
and Broback scored the next 16 points for Minnesota.

"When the guards are able to get even a foot or two feet into
the lane, my defense has to help out, and they're able to find me
or kick it back out," McCarville said.

Linda Sayavongchanh paced Drake with 19 points, Erin Dohrmann
added 16 and Lindsay Whorton scored 12 for the Bulldogs, who
dressed only eight players but refused to fold after a red-hot
start for the Gophers.

Minnesota hit its first eight shots and used a 17-2 run over a
four-minute span to pull out to a 38-17 lead with 5:10 to play in
the half, but the Bulldogs blanked Minnesota the rest of the way,
scoring the final 13 points before the break to cut their deficit
to 38-30.

Sayavongchanh got the Drake run started with a 3-pointer, and
Whorton followed with 3-pointers on consecutive possessions.
Minnesota called a timeout but couldn't get its offense back in
gear -- on their final seven possessions, the Gophers missed three
shots and committed four of their 19 turnovers.

"We went through a stretch where we were very careless with the
ball," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "Then we let our offense
affect our defense, and as a result, they went on an 18-0 run."

McCarville snapped Drake's streak with three inside baskets,
giving Minnesota some momentum before Roysland's burst let the
Gophers pull away for good.

"This is a game of runs, and they'd just made their run,"
Calhoun said. "We knew we needed to make our run, too."
